The east coast of Sardinia is 188 miles long, Sardinia. the west coast 175, the south coast 77 and the north coast 1253 its circumference is 565 miles; and at Cape Carbonara its distance from Africa is 200 miles and from Cadiz 1400. It also has two islands off Capo Falcone called the Islands of Hercules, one off La Punta dell’Alga called Santo Antiocho, and one off Cape Carbonara called Coltelalzo. Near it some authorities also place the island sof Berelis, ι Callodes and the one called the Baths of Hera. The best-known peoples in Sardinia are the Ilienses, Balari, Corsi (who occupy 18 towns), Sulcitani, Valentini, Neapolitani, Vitenses, Caralitam' (who have the Roman citizenship), and the Norenses3 and one colony called At Libiso’s Tower. Sardinia itself was called by Timaeus sandaliotis, from the similarity of its shape to the sole of a shoe, and by Myrsilus Ichnusa, from its resemblance to a footprint. Opposite to the Bay of Paestum is La Licosa, called after the Siren buried there3 and opposite Velia are Pontia and Isacia, both included under the one name of the Oenotrides, which is evidence that Italy was once in the possession of the Oenotri3 and opposite to Vibo are the small islands called the Isles of Ithaca, from the watch-towerc of Ulysses that stands there.
